    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-24T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="791"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d791">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 (D) E.D.B./2261: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-25T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 25, 1943—midnight.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>91. Since the receipt of your telegram no. 18, January 5, 6 p.m.,<note n="73"
                        xml:id="d791fn73">Not printed; it indicated that Chile was about to issue a
                        decree controlling the domestic consumption of copper.</note> the Department
                    and other agencies of this Government have been <pb facs="0839" n="827"
                        xml:id="pg_827"/> awaiting anxiously word from you that the negotiations
                    looking to the limitation of Chilean consumption of copper for manufacture and
                    export had been satisfactorily concluded. The Reconstruction Finance Corporation
                    has pointed out that exports of copper and copper manufactures are now exceeding
                    the 20,000–ton annual goal by approximately 1,000 tons per month. This is a
                    serious loss to United Nations military requirements and further delay in
                    arriving at an agreement can bring only detriment in the prosecution of the war.
                    Please immediately present this case forcefully to the appropriate authorities
                    and spare no effort to follow the negotiation through to a prompt and
                    satisfactory conclusion within the framework we have already set up.</p>
                <p>The Department again repeats the seriousness of this situation. Please reply by
                    telegraph.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
